Research on symbol emergence has explored how discrete categories arise from continuous sensorimotor experience. Prior work has described symbol emergence as a multi-layered process involving individual representation learning, multimodal categorization, and eventually the formation of shared symbol systems within society. Other studies have examined how agents acquire internal categories through interaction and prediction. Our work follows this general line of research but focuses on a more mechanistic question: how symbolic boundaries arise within the latent dynamics of a predictive model, even without multimodality or social interaction.